<li id="cite_note-23"><b><a href="#cite_ref-23" title="">^</a></b> For example, in the "Preface" to <i>A Little Pretty Pocket-Book</i>, Newbery recommended that parents feed their child a “common Diet only, cloath him thin, let him have good Exercise, and be as much exposed to Hardships as his natural Constitution will admit” because “the Face of a child, when it comes into the World, (says the great Mr. Locke) is as tender and susceptible of Injuries as any other Part of the Body; yet by being always exposed, it becomes Proof against the severest Season, and the most inclement Weather.” <i>A Little Pretty Pocket-Book, Intended for the Instruction and Amusement of Little Master Tommy, and Pretty Miss Polly</i>. 10th edition. London: Printed for J. Newbery (1760), 6.</li>
